A few things worth knowing about how Texas handles these claims:

Under Texas Tax Code Section 34.04(b), a claim must be filed within two years of the tax sale date. After that window closes, the funds are distributed to the taxing units and cannot be recovered. The claim is not filed with the county clerk's office; it is filed by petition with the district court that issued the original tax judgment, and the court may schedule a hearing before approving distribution.

If the former owner is deceased, heirs generally need to establish heirship through an affidavit of heirship or a formal probate proceeding before the court will approve a claim on the estate's behalf. Texas does not set a statutory cap on fees for this type of recovery, so if you work with anyone to help file, review the fee terms carefully before signing anything.

We help property owners and eligible claimants gather the required documentation and prepare the petition for {{ county_name }} County's district court. If you have questions about whether you have a valid claim, what documents you will need, or whether anyone else may have a competing interest in the funds, we are glad to walk through it with you.

You are also welcome to contact the district clerk of {{ county_name }} County directly to pursue the claim on your own. There is no obligation to respond to this letter.

